lians 1943–1945 -- t25. Former Forced Labourers as Immigrants in Great Britain after 1945 -- t26. Slave Labour and Shoah -- t27. International Slave and Forced Labour Documentation Project -- t28. Forced and Slave Labour in the Context of the Jewish Holocaust Experience -- tIII -- t29. A Memorial for the Persecuted, Materials for Education and Science -- t30. ‘A moment of elation … and painful’ -- t31. Witnesses at the First Auschwitz Trial in Frankfurt -- t32. Twenty-five Years Later -- t33. It Was Modern Slavery -- tAppendix 1: Interview Guidelines -- tAppendix 2: Timeline -- tAppendix 3: Interview Partners -- tList of Contributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring World War II at least 13.5 million people were employed as forced labourers in Germany and across the territories occupied by the German Reich. Most came from Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, Moldavia, the Baltic countries, France, Poland and Italy. Among them were 8.4 million civilians working for private companies and public agencies in industry, administration and agriculture. In addition, there were 4.6 million prisoners of war and 1.7 million concentration camp prisoners who were either subjected to forced labour in concentration or similar camps or were ‘rented out’ or sold by the SS. While there are numerous publications on forced labour in National Socialist Germany during World War II, this publication combines a historical account of events with the biographies and memories of former forced labourers from twenty-seven countries, offering a comparative international perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aConcentration camp inmateszEuropevBiography. 0aForced laborzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aForced laborzGermanyxHi